 the Kindertransport is remembered both in the countries of origin, particularly Germany, and in the host nations, as well as the first to analyze how it is represented in museums, memorials, and commemorations. Seeing memory of the Kindertransport in the host nations and in Germany as significantly different, the study argues that the different national memory discourses around the Nazi persecution of Jews shape the respective countries' images of the Kindertransport, and that those images in turn shape the discourses - especially in Britain. Yet while national memory frameworks remain crucial to how the Kindertransport is remembered, the book also documents the increasing significance of transnational memory trends that link the host nations with each other and with the countries from which the children originated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust memorials. 0aHolocaust survivorszAustralia. 0aHolocaust survivorszCanada. 0aHolocaust survivorszEngland. 0aHolocaust survivorszUnited States. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945). 0aJewish childrenxHistoryy20th centuryzGermany. 0aKindertransports (Rescue operations)xExhibitions. 0aKindertransports (Rescue operations)zAustralia. 0aKindertransports (Rescue operations)zCanada. 0aKindertransports (Rescue operations)zEngland. 0aKindertransports (Rescue operations)zUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescue. 4aGerman History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aAustralia.  aBritain.  aCanada.  aNazi.  aNew Zealand.  aSecond World War.  aUnited States.  ahost nations.  aperpetrator countries.  apersecution of Jews.1 aNiven, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831